@NODE INTRO "What's a map editor?"
  @{FG SHINE}@{U}@{B}What the Hell's a Map Editor?@{UB}@{UU}@{FG TEXT}

    Basically it's an editor that allows piece smaller chunks of
  graphics to make up a whole screen. In the case of this editor,
  it allows you to piece Blitz2 shapes onto a backdrop of any size
  you find suitable.
  @{I}  e.g. Imagine you have 100 shapes containing the images of paths,
  grass, trees and water. You could piece these together to give the
  impression of a park.@{UI}

    This is a very common method used in 2D scrolling games where the
  play area is very much larger than the screen. As the player walks
  along, new scenery is drawn slightly off screen and scrolled into
  view.
    @{I}e.g. Faery Tale Adventure, Chaos Engine on the Amiga and even more
    modern affairs such as Loaded and Diablo use this style.@{UI}

    Simon's MappED will allow you to create such enormous maps to use
  in your own @{I}(Presumably Blitz2)@{UI} games.

@ENDNODE

@NODE REQUIREMENTS "Can I run this thing?"
  @{FG SHINE}@{U}@{B}Requirements?@{UB}@{UU}@{FG TEXT}

    To be honest I've no idea what other systems it runs under, because I
  know no-one else who owns an Amiga.

    I know in theory what it @{i}should @{ui} run under.

  @{fg highlight}Operating Systems@{fg text}
    @{B}OS 3.0@{UB} or above is required for the Intuition the program uses.

  @{fg highlight}Memory@{fg text}
    @{B}2MB Chip RAM@{UB} is plenty for most map editing. Of course it
  doesn't hurt to have a wad of Fast RAM, but at a push I think this could
  run with just 1MB of Chip RAM.

  @{fg highlight}Processor@{fg text}
    It's a very stable program, but not blindingly fast, as is the way
  of all intuition based programs. Vanilla A1200 users will find this
  sluggish so any processor lower than an 68030 requires patience.
    Works fine and dandy on my '040/40mhz though.

    If it works under a system I haven't mentioned here, or indeed
  if you find any bugs, please write and tell @{"me" LINK ME} about it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE INSTALL "How do I Install this?"
  @{fg highlight}@{B}@{U}Installation@{UU}@{UB}@{fg text}

  Just drag the MappED drawer to wherever you want on your harddisk.
    If you want it to run from floppy then format a disk with an
  install bootblock and expand this archive straight into the root of DF0:

  Make sure you install the following libraries, in @{B}LIBS:@{UB}
   @{FG FILL} asl.library
    diskfont.library
    mathtrans.library
    reqtools.library@{FG TEXT}


  And also copy Dpaint.font into @{B}FONTS:@{UB}
    If you've installed Deluxe Paint on your harddisk it will be
  there already.

    These are fairly common, and you should probably own them already.

  After that, you are ready to run.

    To run the MappED Either:-

    @{I}* Double click on the Workbench Icon
    * Go the the appropriate CLI drawer and type MappED@{UI}

@ENDNODE

@NODE FEATURES "Why's this any good?"
  @{FG SHINE}@{B}@{U}Features...@{UU}@{UB}@{FG TEXT}
    * Everything is Intuition friendly, with Gadtools, ASL and Menus.
    * Menu's mean novices can get quickly to grips with the MappED.
    * Keyboard shortcuts are included for experienced users.
    * Undo and Erase functions.
    * Quick and versitile shape selection.
    * Maps can be drawn with "depths" allowing for foreground and background.
    * 32000x32000 pixels of map. over 100 times the
        standard width and height of a physical lo-res screen.
    * Maps can have an IFF background underlying the them.
    * Saves your last working directories, allowing to quickly re-access
        the last files you were working on.
@ENDNODE

@NODE MAP "The .MAP file format"
  @{FG SHINE}@{U}@{B}Using the .MAP format@{UB}@{UU}@{FG TEXT}
    The standard .MAP format is a fairly simple text file with keywords
  to declare details of the map.
    You can use this description to write the code you need to
  load the map data into you're programs.
    Here is a line by line summary of the .MAP format.

  @{B}* The file begins with a remark declaring the file to be MappED file.@{UB}
    @{I}If the file is in Mki$ format it will be noted after this rem.@{UI}
  @{B}* A remark naming describing the following map.@{UB}
  @{B}* A remark identifying the game/utility the map is intended for.@{UB}
  @{B}* A remark declaring the author of the map.@{UB}
  @{B}* Keyword "WIDTH:"@{UB}
  @{B}* the map's width parameter@{UB}
  @{B}* Keyword "HEIGHT:"@{UB}
  @{B}* the map's height parameter@{UB}
  @{FG FILL}If a background is used in the map add the following...@{FG TEXT}
    @{B}* Keyword "BACK:"@{UB}
    @{B}* the background's AmigaDOS path@{UB}
    @{B}* the background's AmigaDOS filename@{UB}
  @{FG FILL}If a palette used in the map add the following...@{FG TEXT}
    @{B}* Keyword "PALETTE:"@{UB}
    @{B}* the palette's AmigaDOS path@{UB}
    @{B}* the palette's AmigaDOS filename@{UB}
  @{B}* Keyword "SHAPE:"@{UB}
  @{B}* the shape's AmigaDOS path@{UB}
  @{B}* the shape's AmigaDOS filename@{UB}
  @{FG FILL}It's possible for several set of shapes to be defined here@{FG TEXT}
  @{B}* Keyword "MAP:"@{UB}

    Following the keyword MAP: follows is the @{I}map data.@{UI}
  It's simply a list of a shape number, an X co-ord and a Y co-ord.

    If the map is saved in layers you'll see the @{B}Keyword "LAYER "@{UB} plus
  a number for which layer follows. The number begins at one each
  time a new layer starts the number increases.

 @{I} N.B. If the map is saved without notes or layers then only a list of a
  shape number, an X co-ord and a Y co-ord is saved in the file.@{UI}

  @{FG FILL}In the examples/ drawer there is a .MAP file to look at.@{FG TEXT}



@ENDNODE

